               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410510-name-428" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-428" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-428" type="surname" value="HALEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-428" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL HALEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 237.) On the 28th of April, about half-past five o'clock in the morning, I was in William-street, Islington, and saw the prisoner coming out of an unfinished house—I followed him —he kept looking back—I went and asked whether he came out of an un<lb></lb>finished house—he said he did—I saw the handles of the brushes stick<lb></lb>ing out of his pocket—I asked how he came by them—he said he found them in the passage of an unfinished house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410510-name-429" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-429" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-429" type="surname" value="HOOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410510-name-429" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a plumber. I locked these brushes in an un<lb></lb>finished house at four o'clock the previous afternoon—I afterwards found the padlock had been broken off, and some one had got in and taken them—these are my brushes—the prisoner had worked in a brickfield at the back of the premises as a brickmaker.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I came through this house every day from my work—I found these things in the passage, and picked them up, intending to give them to the prosecutor in the morning.</p>
